04246nam a22005175i 9780804783316DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20202012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047833167 a10.1515/97808047833162doi  a(DE-B1597)564859  a(OCoLC)1224278996  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE184.A1bH84 2012eb 7aSOC0310002bisacsh04a305.8009732231 aHughey, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhite Bound :bNationalists, Antiracists, and the Shared Meanings of Race /cMatthew Hughey. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 Racists versus Antiracists? -- tChapter 2 Navigating White Nationalists: National Equality for All -- tChapter 3 Everyday Activities with Antiracists: Whites for Racial Justice -- tChapter 4 White Panic -- tChapter 5 The Ironic Value of Dishonor -- tChapter 6 Saviors and Segregation -- tChapter 7 Color Capital and White Debt -- tChapter 8 Hailing Whiteness -- tChapter 9 Beyond Good and Evil -- tAppendix A. A Primer on Nationalism and Antiracism -- tAppendix B. Research Methodology -- tAppendix C. Notes on Decisions, Difficulty, Development, and Dangers -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDiscussions of race are inevitably fraught with tension, both in opinion and positioning. Too frequently, debates are framed as clear points of opposition-us versus them. And when considering white racial identity, a split between progressive movements and a neoconservative backlash is all too frequently assumed. Taken at face value, it would seem that whites are splintering into antagonistic groups, with differing worldviews, values, and ideological stances. White Bound investigates these dividing lines, questioning the very notion of a fracturing whiteness, and in so doing offers a unique view of white racial identity. Matthew Hughey spent over a year attending the meetings, reading the literature, and interviewing members of two white organizations-a white nationalist group and a white antiracist group. Though he found immediate political differences, he observed surprising similarities. Both groups make meaning of whiteness through a reliance on similar racist and reactionary stories and worldviews. On the whole, this book puts abstract beliefs and theoretical projection about the supposed fracturing of whiteness into relief against the realities of two groups never before directly compared with this much breadth and depth. By examining the similarities and differences between seemingly antithetical white groups, we see not just the many ways of being white, but how these actors make meaning of whiteness in ways that collectively reproduce both white identity and, ultimately, white supremacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAnti-racismzUnited States. 0aRacexSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWhite nationalismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478331640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783316423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804783316.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles